Importance of Secure Software Development Life Cycle
(SDLC) and Security

24.06.2024
In today's world, influenced by digital transformation, software development plays
a critical role across all sectors. In this context, software security is not only the
responsibility of developers but also of the entire team and company. The Secure
Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) aims to enhance the security of software
products by integrating security at every stage.
What is SDLC and Why is it Important?
Traditionally, security tests were conducted in the final stages of the development
process, often leading to the release of insecure code. However, in our world where
technology permeates nearly every aspect of life and the use of artificial intelligence
is rapidly increasing, creating secure software architectures, writing secure code, and
implementing hardware security measures are becoming increasingly important.
Integrating security from the beginning of the process is crucial for increasing control
and predictability and preventing higher costs. In this context, SDLC ensures that
software is more secure and reduces costs by identifying security vulnerabilities early
[1]. Early detection means identifying design flaws before they are coded, which
reduces correction costs. Additionally, risk reduction decreases the intrinsic business
risks and increases security awareness among all stakeholders [2].
How to Implement Secure SDLC?
Successfully implementing a Secure Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC)
requires integrating security tests and other critical security activities into existing
development processes. This process has three main components: defining security
requirements, conducting architectural risk analysis, and using code scanning tools.
The first step in Secure SDLC is defining security requirements alongside functional
requirements. This stage helps reduce security risks at the start of the software
development and contributes to creating more secure software. For instance,
specifying that users can only view their information is crucial. Clearly defining
security requirements ensures that security vulnerabilities are minimized throughout
the software's life cycle [3].
During the design phase, it is necessary to conduct an architectural risk analysis. This
analysis evaluates the design from a security perspective and identifies potential
security vulnerabilities early. Architectural risk analysis plays a critical role in
identifying security threats at an early stage and taking measures against them. Thus,
the security of the software is enhanced from the design phase.
In the coding process, using code scanning tools is a vital part of Secure SDLC. Tools
such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and interactive application security testing
are used to detect and resolve security vulnerabilities. These tools provide developers
with immediate feedback on the security status of the code they write, ensuring the
code is secure. Particularly, static application security testing (SAST) and dynamic
application security testing (DAST) are effective methods for detecting and
addressing security vulnerabilities [2].
In addition to these fundamental practices and requirements, it is important for
stakeholders to receive up-to-date information and training on SDLC and its
applications. Ongoing risk analyses and test planning should also be considered to
increase the success rate of the projects.
In conclusion, SDLC practices help reduce costs by identifying security
vulnerabilities early in the software development process and increasing the overall
security of the software .
